We had a bug recently in Service Desk because the Issue property indexing code is negatively caching that fact that we have no IndexDocumentConfiguration entries - but we do.
The code then ignored out issue properties during a re-index because the cache said there was no config.
CachingPluginIndexConfigurationManager is the cuplrit.
It has these invalidation events

{code}
@EventListener
public void onClearCache(final ClearCacheEvent event)
{ byEntityKeyCache.removeAll(); }
@PluginEventListener
public void onPluginUninstalled(final PluginUninstalledEvent event)
{ remove(event.getPlugin().getKey()); }

@PluginEventListener
public void onPluginRefreshed(final PluginRefreshedEvent event)
{ remove(event.getPlugin().getKey()); }
@PluginEventListener
public void onPluginUpgraded(final PluginUpgradedEvent event)
{ remove(event.getPlugin().getKey()); }
{code}

they are not good enough. They miss key events .

There is a timing aspect to this. During automated tests its possible that issue re-indexes can happen WHILE the IndexDocumentConfiguration is yet to be declared and once that happens the computation is held until an invalid invalidation event happens.

Or this might not happen in which case our tests pass.

DefaultPluginModuleTracker is a good class to use to track modules of a certain type turning up or not.

